{"sections":[],"abstract":[{"text":"Read the notation that the formal grammar uses.","type":"text"}],"metadata":{"title":"About the Language Reference"},"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/org.swift.tspl\/documentation\/The-Swift-Programming-Language\/AboutTheLanguageReference"},"kind":"article","primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This part of the book describes the formal grammar of the Swift programming language.","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"The grammar described here is intended to help you understand the language in more"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"detail, rather than to allow you to directly implement a parser or compiler.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The Swift language is relatively small, because many common types, functions, and operators"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"that appear virtually everywhere in Swift code"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"are actually defined in the Swift standard library. Although these types, functions,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"and operators aren’t part of the Swift language itself,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"they’re used extensively in the discussions and code examples in this part of the book.","type":"text"}]},{"text":"How to Read the Grammar","anchor":"How-to-Read-the-Grammar","level":2,"type":"heading"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The notation used to describe the formal grammar of the Swift programming language"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"follows a few conventions:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"An arrow (→) is used to mark grammar productions and can be read as “can consist of.”","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Syntactic categories are indicated by "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"italic","type":"text"}]},{"text":" text and appear on both sides","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"of a grammar production rule.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Literal words and punctuation are indicated by "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"code":"boldface constant width","type":"codeVoice"}]},{"type":"text","text":" text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and appear only on the right-hand side of a grammar production rule."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Alternative grammar productions are separated by vertical","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"bars (|). When alternative productions are too long to read easily,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"they’re broken into multiple grammar production rules on new lines."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In a few cases, regular font text is used to describe the right-hand side","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"of a grammar production rule."}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Optional syntactic categories and literals are marked by a trailing","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"question mark, ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"?","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}]}],"type":"unorderedList"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"As an example, the grammar of a getter-setter block is defined as follows:","type":"text"}]},{"style":"note","name":"Grammar of a getter-setter block","type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-setter-block"}]},{"type":"text","text":" → "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"{"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"getter-clause","type":"text"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"setter-clause","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"?"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"}"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":" | ","type":"text"},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"{"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"setter-clause","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-clause"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"}"}]}]}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This definition indicates that a getter-setter block can consist of a getter clause"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"followed by an optional setter clause, enclosed in braces,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"or","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":" a setter clause followed by a getter clause, enclosed in braces."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"The grammar production above is equivalent to the following two productions,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"where the alternatives are spelled out explicitly:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"name":"Grammar of a getter-setter block","type":"aside","style":"note","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-setter-block"}]},{"type":"text","text":" → "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"code":"{","type":"codeVoice"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-clause"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"setter-clause","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"?","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"}"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"\n"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-setter-block"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" → "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"{"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"setter-clause","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"getter-clause","type":"text"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"code":"}","type":"codeVoice"}]}]}]}],"kind":"content"}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/org.swift.tspl\/documentation\/The-Swift-Programming-Language"]]},"schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"major":0,"minor":3},"references":{"doc://org.swift.tspl/documentation/The-Swift-Programming-Language":{"kind":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/org.swift.tspl\/documentation\/The-Swift-Programming-Language","role":"collection","url":"\/documentation\/the-swift-programming-language","abstract":[],"type":"topic","title":"The Swift Programming Language (5.9.2)"}}}